Note:
============================================================================
P2-B DISPATCHER API SURFACE — Darwin-specific BSD-syscall-number procs
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
These six BSD-syscall-number procs complete the 66-proc bare-name dispatcher
API surface on darwin_x86_64. Five of the six (SYS_EXIT_GROUP, SYS_BRK,
SYS_GETCWD, SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME, SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY) name Linux/SysV syscalls
that do NOT exist as distinct BSD-class entries in XNU; SYS_CREAT is the only
one in this group that has a direct Darwin BSD syscall (entry 8). Each
Darwin-missing proc returns either (a) the BSD number of the closest
semantically-equivalent native syscall, or (b) the -1 runtime sentinel that
`is_error` recognizes, accompanied by a callsite-visible `Note:` documenting
which Mach trap or libsystem function should be used instead.

Specific routing rationale per proc:
  SYS_EXIT_GROUP -> 1: Darwin has no exit_group; BSD `exit` (entry 1)
    terminates the whole task because XNU collapses the task on the last
    thread, achieving the same semantic. Source: xnu/bsd/kern/syscalls.master
    entry 1 ("exit"); xnu/osfmk/kern/task.c task_terminate semantics.
  SYS_BRK -> -1: XNU has no `brk`/`sbrk` syscall. Heap expansion must use
    BSD `mmap` (197) with MAP_PRIVATE|MAP_ANONYMOUS or Mach `vm_allocate`
    (negative Mach-class trap). Source: xnu/bsd/kern/syscalls.master (no
    `brk` entry); xnu/osfmk/vm/vm_user.c (`vm_allocate` trap).
  SYS_CREAT -> 8: Darwin retains the historical BSD `creat(2)` syscall as
    entry 8. Libc typically rewrites this to `open(O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_TRUNC)`
    but the direct kernel entry remains. Source: xnu/bsd/kern/syscalls.master
    entry 8 ("creat").
  SYS_GETCWD -> -1: `getcwd` on Darwin is libsystem-only (Libc-1583.x.x/gen/
    FreeBSD/getcwd.c); XNU exports no stable BSD-class syscall. Callers must
    bridge via `fcntl(F_GETPATH)` on the cwd descriptor or via Phase 8 FFI
    to libsystem. Source: absence of `getcwd` entry in xnu/bsd/kern/
    syscalls.master; Apple Developer Path Resolution documentation.
  SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME -> 116: XNU exposes `clock_gettime(2)` only via libsystem;
    the closest pure BSD syscall is `gettimeofday(2)` at entry 116. Nanosecond-
    precision callers must use Mach `mach_absolute_time` (Mach trap 0x1000027,
    negative class) with `mach_timebase_info`. Source: xnu/bsd/kern/
    syscalls.master entry 116 ("gettimeofday"); xnu/osfmk/mach/mach_traps.h
    (`_mach_absolute_time` trap); Libc-1583.x.x/gen/clock_gettime.c.
  SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY -> -1: No BSD-class equivalent on Darwin. CPU
    affinity is expressed via Mach `thread_policy_set` with
    THREAD_AFFINITY_POLICY (negative Mach class, hint not guarantee); CPU
    count is queried via `host_processor_info` or `sysctlbyname("hw.activecpu")`.
    Source: xnu/osfmk/mach/thread_policy.h (THREAD_AFFINITY_POLICY); Apple
    Technical Q&A QA1670 (Affinity API).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each proc is a nullary `Process` returning the constant Integer that the
bare-name dispatcher's `<NAME> from Syscall` lookup will resolve to on
darwin_x86_64 targets. Procs returning a valid BSD syscall number (1, 8, 116)
are intended to be passed directly to `syscall_N` wrappers; those callers will
then have the BSD class mask `0x2000000` OR'd into RAX by the inline assembly
in the generic dispatcher (`syscall_0` through `syscall_8`). Procs returning
-1 are runtime sentinels: their bare-name lookup succeeds (no link error), but
any caller forwarding the result to a `syscall_N` wrapper will trigger the
inline assembly path with RAX = 0x2000000 | -1 = 0x1FFFFFF, an invalid syscall
number that XNU rejects with -ENOSYS. The recommended call pattern is to
gate every Darwin-missing op behind an `is_error(SYS_X())` check before
issuing the syscall, OR to never bind these names on Darwin code paths
(i.e. the runtime calls Mach traps / FFI libsystem directly).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
All six procs are constant-return; the compiler is expected to inline them at
every call site (HIR -> MIR constant-fold pass) leaving zero call overhead.
Do not introduce conditionals, side effects, or runtime computation in these
bodies. The -1 sentinel branch in caller code should be evaluated at the
caller's hot-path entry, not inside the SYS_X getter, so that the inliner can
fold both the SYS_X return and the `is_error` check into a single comparison.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a syscall number carries no privilege; the BSD class mask is applied
later by `syscall_N`. Callers must not assume that a non-negative return
value guarantees the syscall is implementable on the running Darwin version:
syscalls.master content varies between XNU versions (numbers stable since
macOS 10.13, but availability of e.g. `__mac_*` traps depends on kernel
build flags). Returning -1 is explicitly a contract that the proc is
unsupported on Darwin and any caller proceeding to issue the syscall will
receive -ENOSYS from the kernel; this is the correct failure mode because it
forces the caller to take the Darwin-native path (Mach trap or libsystem FFI)
rather than silently issuing an invalid syscall and corrupting RAX.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "darwin_x86_64_SYS_EXIT_GROUP" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Aliases BSD exit (entry 1); XNU task_terminate collapses on last thread
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_SYS_BRK" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: No BSD brk syscall on Darwin — use syscall_mmap with MAP_ANONYMOUS
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_SYS_CREAT" returns Integer:
    Return 8  Note: xnu/bsd/kern/syscalls.master entry 8 (creat)
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_SYS_GETCWD" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: libsystem-only on Darwin — use fcntl(F_GETPATH) or Phase 8 FFI
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_SYS_CLOCK_GETTIME" returns Integer:
    Return 116  Note: Aliases BSD gettimeofday (entry 116); use mach_absolute_time for ns precision
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_SYS_SCHED_GETAFFINITY" returns Integer:
    Return -1  Note: No BSD equivalent — use Mach thread_policy_set or sysctlbyname("hw.activecpu")
End Process

Note:
============================================================================
GENERIC SYSCALL WRAPPERS
============================================================================
Darwin x86_64 syscall convention:
- RAX = syscall number (BSD syscalls need 0x2000000 mask)
- RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9 = arguments 1-6
- Stack = arguments 7+ (16-byte aligned)
- Return value in RAX
:End Note

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_0" takes syscall_number as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 0 arguments
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Execute syscall (Darwin x86_64 uses syscall instruction)
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_1" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 1 argument
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load argument 1 into RDI
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-24], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_2" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 2 arguments
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load arguments into RDI, RSI
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-32], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_3" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 3 arguments
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load arguments into RDI, RSI, RDX
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-40], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_4" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 4 arguments
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load arguments into RDI, RSI, RDX, R10
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-48], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_5" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 5 arguments
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load arguments into RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]
        mov r8, [rbp-48]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-56], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_6" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 6 arguments
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load arguments into RDI, RSI, RDX, R10, R8, R9
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]
        mov r8, [rbp-48]
        mov r9, [rbp-56]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-64], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_7" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer, arg7 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 7 arguments (arg7 passed on stack)
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load arguments 1-6 into registers
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]
        mov r8, [rbp-48]
        mov r9, [rbp-56]

        # Argument 7 already on stack at [rbp-64]
        push [rbp-64]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Clean up stack
        add rsp, 8

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-72], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_8" takes syscall_number as Integer, arg1 as Integer, arg2 as Integer, arg3 as Integer, arg4 as Integer, arg5 as Integer, arg6 as Integer, arg7 as Integer, arg8 as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Darwin x86_64 syscall with 8 arguments (args 7-8 passed on stack)
    Applies BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000) for macOS compatibility
    :End Note
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        # Load syscall number into RAX
        mov rax, [rbp-8]

        # Apply BSD syscall class mask (0x2000000)
        or rax, 0x2000000

        # Load arguments 1-6 into registers
        mov rdi, [rbp-16]
        mov rsi, [rbp-24]
        mov rdx, [rbp-32]
        mov r10, [rbp-40]
        mov r8, [rbp-48]
        mov r9, [rbp-56]

        # Arguments 7-8 on stack (reverse order for stack pushing)
        push [rbp-72]
        push [rbp-64]

        # Execute syscall
        syscall

        # Clean up stack
        add rsp, 16

        # Store result from RAX
        mov [rbp-80], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

