Note:
============================================================================
DISPATCHER-NAMED SYSCALL WRAPPERS (Wave 1 backfill)
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
These three high-level wrappers complete the 66-proc dispatcher API surface for
darwin_x86_64. `syscall_fstat` and `syscall_lseek` are direct BSD-syscall
forwarders for entries 189 (fstat) and 199 (lseek) — both routinely available
on Darwin and following the standard register-arg convention used by every
other `syscall_<name>` wrapper in this file. `syscall_brk` is a sentinel
wrapper that short-circuits on the -1 returned by SYS_BRK (see the
@Reasoning block on SYS_BRK above): Darwin has no `brk(2)` syscall, so the
wrapper must not attempt to issue syscall number -1 (which after the
0x2000000 mask becomes 0x1FFFFFF, an undefined kernel entry). Callers reach
syscall_brk for cross-platform-portable heap initialization; the -1 return
signals "unsupported on this platform, use mmap instead", matching the
contract documented on SYS_BRK.
Source: xnu/bsd/kern/syscalls.master entries 189 (fstat) and 199 (lseek);
absence of `brk` entry in syscalls.master; Darwin libsystem getrlimit(2)
documentation noting "use mmap for heap expansion."
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
`syscall_fstat` and `syscall_lseek` resolve the BSD syscall number via the
already-defined SYS_FSTAT()/SYS_LSEEK() accessors and forward to syscall_2 /
syscall_3 respectively. The generic dispatcher applies the 0x2000000 BSD-class
mask to RAX inside inline assembly, so these wrappers do not need to do so
themselves. `syscall_brk` resolves SYS_BRK() (which returns -1 on Darwin),
guards against the unsupported-syscall sentinel with `If syscall_num is less
than 0`, and returns -1 directly without ever executing the `syscall`
instruction. Were Darwin to gain a brk(2) syscall in a future XNU release, the
SYS_BRK constant would change from -1 to the positive entry number and this
wrapper would automatically begin issuing the syscall.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
The unsupported-syscall guard in `syscall_brk` is the only branch and is
expected to be branch-predictor-friendly: on Darwin SYS_BRK is a compile-time
constant -1, so MIR constant-fold will reduce the wrapper to `Return -1`
unconditionally at every Darwin call site. `syscall_fstat` and `syscall_lseek`
are pure forwarders with no branches; their overhead is one indirect arg-load
plus the `syscall` instruction itself. None of these three wrappers should
allocate, lock, or block in userland; all kernel-side blocking is the
responsibility of the underlying syscall.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
`syscall_fstat` operates on a caller-supplied file descriptor and pointer to a
`struct stat` buffer; the caller is responsible for ensuring the buffer is
writable for at least sizeof(struct stat) bytes (144 bytes on Darwin 64-bit
with the post-10.6 `stat64` layout). The kernel validates the fd; an invalid
fd yields -EBADF. `syscall_lseek` is purely fd-positional and carries no
data-validity risk beyond the standard fd lifetime contract; SEEK_END on a
non-seekable file descriptor (pipe, socket) yields -ESPIPE. `syscall_brk` on
Darwin is a no-op returning -1 and therefore carries no security state.
Callers must treat negative returns from any of these wrappers as syscall
errors via `is_error`.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note:
    Set program break (Darwin: not supported as a native syscall)
    Returns -1 sentinel; callers must use syscall_mmap with MAP_ANONYMOUS.
    :End Note
    Let syscall_num be darwin_x86_64_SYS_BRK()
    If syscall_num is less than 0:
        Return -1
    End If
    Return darwin_x86_64_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file status by descriptor (Darwin BSD syscall 189)
    Let syscall_num be darwin_x86_64_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return darwin_x86_64_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reposition file offset (Darwin BSD syscall 199)
    Let syscall_num be darwin_x86_64_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return darwin_x86_64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_syscall_ioctl" takes fd as Integer, cmd as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Dispatcher-API entry-point for POSIX ioctl(2) on Darwin x86_64.
    SYS_ioctl is 54 (Darwin XNU bsd/kern/syscalls.master, shared
    Mach/BSD personality entry 54). Three-arg shape (fd, request,
    argp). The Darwin x86_64 calling convention uses the standard
    System V argument registers (rdi, rsi, rdx) and the syscall
    instruction with the BSD class bit (0x2000000) ORed into the
    syscall number (handled by darwin_x86_64_syscall_3).
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Composes the syscall by calling darwin_x86_64_SYS_IOCTL() (returns
    54) and darwin_x86_64_syscall_3(54, fd, cmd, arg). The BSD class
    bit is applied inside the syscall_N helper before the syscall
    instruction is executed.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    O(1) dispatch in XNU — one FD-table lookup and a driver vtable
    jump. Terminal-related ioctls (TCGETS, TIOCGWINSZ) are cheap
    memcpy-from-tty operations on Darwin and translate directly to
    the BSD ttydriver's equivalents.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    XNU validates fd against the per-process FD table and dispatches
    cmd through the device's fileops.fo_ioctl vtable. arg, if a
    pointer, is dereferenced by the kernel with the structure size
    implied by cmd; callers must size the buffer to match. Darwin's
    sandbox profile may also intercept ioctl(2) for unprivileged
    processes — callers should expect EPERM in sandboxed contexts.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let syscall_num be darwin_x86_64_SYS_IOCTL()
    Return darwin_x86_64_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, cmd, arg)
End Process

