Note:
============================================================================
FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
============================================================================
:End Note

@Reasoning
File mode constants exposed by the cross-platform dispatcher's bare-name API.
Darwin uses the same `mode_t` encoding as every POSIX system: the low 9 bits
are the rwxrwxrwx permission triplet, encoded octally as 0644 (rw-r--r--) and
0755 (rwxr-xr-x). The values below are the decimal equivalents of those octal
constants, as required by the BSD syscall ABI which treats the mode argument
as a plain integer. The bit layout (S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200, S_IRGRP=0040,
S_IWGRP=0020, S_IROTH=0004, S_IWOTH=0002, S_IXUSR=0100, S_IXGRP=0010,
S_IXOTH=0001) is identical on Darwin, Linux, and the BSDs because it predates
the POSIX standard and was inherited from the original 4.3BSD `sys/stat.h`.
0644 = 0400|0200|0040|0004 = 420 decimal. 0755 = 0400|0200|0100|0040|0010|
0004|0001 = 493 decimal.
Source: xnu/bsd/sys/stat.h (S_IR*/S_IW*/S_IX* macros); POSIX.1-2017 chmod(2)
mode argument specification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value.
The dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` lookup resolves to this proc on
darwin_x86_64 targets via the bare-name route established in Wave 1.
Wave 2 will rename to `darwin_x86_64_MODE_0644`; Wave 1 keeps the bare form
to match the still-bare dispatcher.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
These accessors are constant returns; the compiler is expected to inline
them at every call site, leaving zero call overhead. Do not introduce any
runtime computation here.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file permission constant carries no security state. Callers who
use the returned value as a `mode` argument to `creat`/`open(O_CREAT)`/
`mkdir`/`chmod` are responsible for ensuring the requested permission
matches the intended access policy. World-readable (0644) is appropriate
for non-sensitive files; group-and-world-executable (0755) is appropriate
for binaries and directories. Darwin additionally applies the per-process
`umask` to the requested mode, so the effective on-disk permission may be
more restrictive than the value passed; callers requiring an exact mode
must call `umask(0)` before the creating syscall.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "darwin_x86_64_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0644 octal = rw-r--r--
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_PROT_NONE" returns Integer:
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_PROT_READ" returns Integer:
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_PROT_WRITE" returns Integer:
    Return 2
End Process

Process called "darwin_x86_64_PROT_EXEC" returns Integer:
    Return 4
End Process

